A picture to understand: Bitcoin's legal status around the world
Abstract: In addition to the price correction naturally caused by speculative properties, the current round of digital currency crash is also related to the "old enemy" - regulatory risks.
Judging from the visual map, Eastern countries are more conservative towards Bitcoin than the West, and the countries that account for the majority of the world are still waiting to see the legitimacy of digital currency, which means that the "black swan risk" is still very large.
*This article is from Wall Street News (WeChat ID: wallstreetcn), edited by Wang Mu. For more information, please visit the wallstreetcn.com or download the Wall Street News app. *
With the regulatory storm in major Bitcoin markets such as China, South Korea and the European Union, the global digital currency led by Bitcoin has suffered a bloodbath this week, with the price of Bitcoin falling below the psychological integer of $10,000 on Tuesday and the biggest one-day decline in three years.
In addition to the price correction naturally caused by speculative properties, this round of digital currency crash is also related to the long-standing "old enemy" - regulatory risks.
At this important juncture, the visual big data website HowMuch.net produced a map showing the legitimacy and regulation of Bitcoin in various countries around the world.
As you can see in the chart below, green represents the legitimate market for Bitcoin, orange represents a neutral market that has not yet publicly legalized its status but has no major restrictions on its use, pale pink represents a restricted market where local governments are trying to approach the use of digital currencies through redline policies or regulations, dark pink represents countries where Bitcoin is defined as illegal, and gray is a country that has not yet commented.
(Above HowMuch.Net image from the visualization team on January 15)
The article points out that from the distribution of non-green color blocks in the figure, it can be seen that the traditional Eastern countries have a more conservative attitude towards Bitcoin than the West.
Russia is currently the largest country to define Bitcoin as illegal, China is one of the largest restricted markets for Bitcoin, and India is one of the largest countries that have not yet commented on Bitcoin and have no policies in place.
North America and Western Europe are the regions with the highest acceptance of Bitcoin, i.e., the distribution of green blocks is more concentrated.
Views on Bitcoin are clearly divided across the Middle East and Latin America, with a more mixed distribution of color patches in these regions.
Among them, Iraq, Iran, Turkey, and Brazil are all legitimate bitcoin markets, while Afghanistan, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Bolivia, etc. have a certain degree of restrictions on their trading and use, and more Latin American countries have not yet spoken out about bitcoin.
Based on the above data, it can be seen that a total of 99 countries (or 40%) of the 246 countries in the world do not impose restrictions on the trading and use of bitcoin, that is, green and orange regions.
Seven countries (or 3%) have restricted markets (pale pink), 10 countries (or 4%) define Bitcoin as illegal (dark pink), and 130 countries (or 53%) have no more information about digital currencies (gray).
This shows that the countries that account for the main body of the world (53%, more than half) are still waiting to see the legitimacy of digital currencies led by Bitcoin in their territories, and it also represents that the "black swan risk" of Bitcoin is still very large, because some of these countries may eventually make legislative decisions to restrict digital currencies.
The article argues that global regulators have not yet fully understood the emerging category of digital currency, which may be the main reason why most countries have not yet made a statement.
Although Bitcoin's "popularity" has grown exponentially since last year, it does not mean that all countries are interested, and some countries may be worried about the threat of local fiat currencies as a result, or more worried about digital currencies being exploited by criminal organizations.
Wall Street Insider has written a detailed summary of the international regulatory news against Bitcoin since last week, including China's crackdown on centralized online platforms and mobile apps for OTC-like exchanges, South Korea's ongoing consideration of shutting down digital currency exchanges, and the European Union's belief that Bitcoin has not yet been widely accepted and warns investors of the risk of "losing all their money".
The editor-in-chief of Wall Street News has mentioned that from the perspective of supervision, acceptance/criticism, and adoption, 2018 will become the first year of digital currency for global central banks.
Russia and other major countries criticize Bitcoin's legitimacy in order to make way for the official issuance of digital currency.
