Block critics on Facebook: If you can't stand the blame of voters, don't run for office
Our Founding Fathers understood the style of bad media.
Americans love Washington, but it wasn't long before the major newspapers began lashing out at him for everything from domestic policies to political principles.
He was annoyed by the criticisms, no doubt.
But he did not silence these critics.
For as early as 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech is taken away – and we are slaughtered like lambs in silence and ignorance." ”
It reminds me of Maryland's Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to learn from Washington.
Hogan's staff blocked and deleted at least 450 people's posts for posting their views on his official Facebook page.
The American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit against him earlier this week.
The governor's staff dismissed the lawsuit as sloppy, and online reports were rife with their outcry: "Who cares?"
A lot of people say, "It's just Facebook." ”
But, it's important.
This is especially important because you're dealing with someone like Hogan.
This is a Republican who serves as governor in a democratic-majority state, and he's surprisingly popular.
He received the second-highest praise among the nation's 50 governors.
Hogan was not a reactionary impatient.
He was in charge of Maryland smoothly and strictly followed the rules.
He is also very adept at using Facebook as his primary way of connecting with his constituents, playfully showing his post-chemotherapy baldness for the first time on his homepage.
So blocking people who come to the governor's homepage to comment is completely unnecessary and ultimately dangerous. This homepage is a public forum and an official management platform advertised by the public's tax-paid staff.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Amelia Schass, a spokeswoman for Hogan, defended the governor's actions, saying she believed that blocking their comments was nothing more than an attempt to get them to refrain a little.
But they are too hasty to describe it as a flood beast or a cynic sweeping the web.
The Washington Post spoke face-to-face with people who had been blocked by Hogan.
They're just ordinary people talking to their elected leaders: teachers, small business owners, and pastors, not some kind of beast.
They all said that their comments were in-depth, respectful, and not lewd.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, calling on Hogan to remember his Catholic faith.
Lakshmi Salma Ramani, a barrister from Maryland Bowie, was not cynical, but she asked questions about hate crimes.
She wrote in the Washington Post's News Story Comments section, "I politely commented that I was disappointed that he didn't respond to hate crimes and other recent news events.
I also don't like a group of people commenting on the same topic, because these people will be directly ignored by some people, thinking that they are a so-called herd mentality, rather than treating them as a group of citizens who are worried about the country and the people. ”
What the governor's staff calls "intensive spam bombardment" may seem to others as "sticking to the word."
The Facebook era has made it easy to modify a message by simply blocking a detractor or deleting a negative comment.
And the clean-up is much cleaner than in the past, when staff were sent out to collect and burn critical newspapers or protesters arrested or silenced.
But that's really what's happening right now, but on a digital level.
Hogan is not the first public official to be blamed for silencing others on Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users for blocking them on Twitter.
A landmark ruling emerged in Virginia last week on such issues.
According to District Judge James C. Kacharis in Alexandria, the chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by blocking voters from her Facebook page.
Kentucky Gov. Matt Bevan (R) has also been patronized by the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be so hard.
In Washington's era, affordable postage and the Internet had a similar impact.
The number of newspapers quadrupled between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letters were written violently criticizing his leadership.
And even at that time, Washington had an anonymous flood beast against him.
Pseudonyms such as Eurekla, Valerius, Belisarius, and Bojus were written to the newspaper to harshly criticize Washington's decision-making.
His office was inundated with petitions criticizing his attitude toward the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation between His Majesty the King and the United States of America, which was signed with Great Britain, according to historical documents collected by the George Washington Newspaper Online Project.
But he didn't silence them.
Freedom of speech, freedom of dissent, and freedom of speech are the foundation of this country.
And true leaders need to accept that.
