Poverty and death in Golden State, Indonesia
Badtina Daijay doesn't use a stove when she cooks.
She rarely even uses a pot.
Her wooden house is located in Enarotali, the capital of Paniyai county in Indonesia's Papua province, where the housewife usually just puts a sweet potato — known locally as "nota" — directly into the fire.
Half an hour later, the burnt sweet potato was eagerly taken out by a pair of unwashed hands and devoured.
Dai Jie sat on the dirt floor—she had no furniture, and this was where she did her daily household chores, such as doing laundry, which was muddy and got from a nearby swamp.
There is a bucket in a room without a roof, and this is the outdoor toilet.
She was the youngest of her husband's four wives, so she was not assigned to the fields to take care of her.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, it was dangerous to work late at night: most of the men in the village were unemployed, and many were drunk, plus there were a lot of soldiers here.
"No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m.," she said. ”
It's a rare glimpse of everyday life in the Papua Highlands, a former Dutch colony that was incorporated into Indonesia after a 1969 referendum, but that referendum was also controversial when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by show of hands in front of the troops occupying the area.
The current strong campaign for independence against Dutch rule soon turned its finger at the Jakarta government, which imposed repressive rule over the region and isolated foreign journalists and activists.
In 2003, the province was officially split into the provinces of Papua and West Papua, while Papua New Guinea independently controlled the eastern part of the island.
Ena Rotali is remote and inhospitable, and it's a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital, Jayapura, to Nabira, followed by a five-hour rental car.
There is no public transport here.
In this town of about 19,000 people, wooden houses are surrounded by bamboo fences, and the folded tin roofs are various yellow-brown coverings made of rust.
Very few Indonesians come to China, let alone journalists, and there are almost no foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian preachers, me Pago Papuans believed in a god called Uga Tame.
There are other changes here as well.
Dai Jie said: "We are not used to wearing these clothes. She was referring to her brightly colored hand-woven bandana, dark blouse and bright skirt.
"We used to cover our bodies only with leaves. ”
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, where 28% of the population lives below the poverty line, and has the highest infant mortality rate and the lowest literacy rate in Asia.
But this is also the golden continent of Indonesia.
Located in the highlands, Paniai County is about the same size as New Jersey and is home to 153,000 people. The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Glasberg, is only 60 miles away, and is owned by Phoenix-based Philip McMoRan Copper & Gold.
In 2015 alone, Phillips mined approximately $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua is rich in timber resources, with an estimated value of $78 billion.
However, these abundant resources are also a source of tragedy for the Papuans, which has enabled Indonesia's strong military to keep them at bay.
A 2005 New York Times investigative report revealed that Philip paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and troops between 1998 and 2004, a whopping $150,000 for officials alone.
The Papuans' growing demand for independence threatened the patron, who was subjected to cruel treatment.
Since 1969, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed, and thousands have been raped, tortured, and imprisoned by the Indonesian military, according to activists.
According to the Asian Commission for Human Rights, mass massacres in the Papuan tribal highlands in the 1970s have escalated into genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters.
A 2016 report by the Catholic Archdiocese of Brisbane, "We Will Lose Everything," contains evidence of the previous year's most egregious abuses, such as extrajudicial executions, torture – another report says rape and electrocution were particularly common – and a brutal crackdown on peaceful demonstrations.
Andreas Halsono, an Indonesia researcher at Human Rights Watch, said: "Violence happens every day, so it's hard to count the number of victims." ”
Papua's resources attracted a large number of immigrants from outside Indonesia, and the oppression began.
Eighty-three percent of the province's population of 3.5 million are Christians, but the demographics of the province changed when Muslim economic migrants arrived from the densely populated islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra, and Sulawesi.
Javanese food stalls sell fried chicken and vegetable mixed gadogado with peanut butter.
The locals fought hard.
Apos You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the provincial capital of Jayapura to find work, explains: "Those immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables at a lower price than the local Papuans in traditional markets.
This has deprived the local Papuans – the Papuan women (mama-mama) – of their market. ”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo (popularly known as Jokowi) vowed during his 2014 campaign to address inequality and abuse of power in Papua.
The former carpenter's path to the Jakarta Presidential Palace is supported by 27 of the 29 districts – including Paniai.
But nothing has changed in Papua, and today, the locals feel betrayed.
"We are heartbroken, and in 2014 we voted for Jokowi in the hope that he would fulfill our wish and restore fairness," Yu said. ”
In fact, just two months after Jokowi took office in October, Pania suffered his worst nightmare.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children in Ena Rotali were singing Christmas carols outside in front of a bonfire when two Indonesian soldiers suddenly rushed over on motorcycles.
The frightened children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to the local priest, Yawit Tebai, one of the soldiers was dissatisfied with their tone and subsequently returned with four soldiers.
Victims and witnesses said the drunk soldiers were chasing the children with their guns.
Then one of the soldiers opened fire on the group of children.
16-year-old Julianus Yemo was beaten badly and fell into a coma.
A few hours later, a raging fire broke out in the building of the Election Commission of a nearby government agency, and the incident escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered at a football pitch in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
Armed with ceremonial hunting bows, they do the waita dance of the Papuan me Pago tribe – running in circles and mimicking birdsong.
Some protesters began throwing stones at regular military posts.
According to an official document seen by Time magazine, when emotions continued to intensify, the soldiers received an order via internal radio: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot immediately." But the document was not released to the local media.
Yeremias Kayamu, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighborhood in Enarotali, sensed impending danger and called on the crowd to calm down and begged them to go home.
But no one was in the mood to listen to him.
Standing on the porch of his brightly colored wooden house, he told Time magazine, "When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in the left wrist. ”
Kayam still doesn't know who fired the shot, but he said the bullet came from among the gathered soldiers.
He added: "It was crowded, they fired a lot of shots. ”
According to a cousin of a local, Olfuus Yule, he witnessed the shooting and saw Ofjus Yule being shot three times.
Juhanes sadly told Time magazine, "I ran over to check his body to see if it was him,
I found out he was dead...... I kissed him. ”
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yuje Mende told reporters that his subordinates were only "protecting" the police station because it had been attacked.
In 2015, Papua Police spokesman and Police Chief Pugio Sulistio said, "When someone threatens to kill us, we have to defend ourselves."
It's a matter of life and death. ”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
The next day, news of the killing spread slowly only in Jakarta.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an impassioned speech in Jayapura in which he expressed deep sympathy for the victims' families and vowed to address the legacy of Papua's history of abuse.
"I hope that this case will be resolved as soon as possible so that it will not happen again in the future," he said. ”
In October 2016, Security Minister Vilando said he wanted to set up a non-judicial mechanism to address the historical problem of human rights violations.
But the excuse for shirk also sounded almost immediately.
"Most of the violations took place a long time ago," he said.
Some were in the 90s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to addressing these violations, but this will require a process. ”
Then on June 5 in Jakarta, Vilando went back on his word during a conversation with Time magazine, saying that he had no plans to establish a grievance mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, "Everything will be settled according to the law." ”
The United Nations has filed charges against Wilando for "crimes against human rights" in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people in the bloody independence votes in East Timor in 1999, but he said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua have been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of the Paniai incident scoffed at these claims.
"I've had four interviews in the last three years, but things haven't progressed at all," Juhanes said. ”
Years later, he said, "I'm tired. ”
He still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he said.
I was afraid of being arrested by the army, I was afraid of being shot. ”
His brother Yukabus also thought that the people of Paniai were afraid to talk about the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury four victims.
"After burying the body, the military came looking for me," he said. ”
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in Deyai district, a neighboring county in Pani Ai.
A construction company manager refused to help transport an unconscious man to the hospital, and the two sides clashed, one died and 17 others were injured, including children.
Lavianus Dovu, a 24-year-old man, died on his way to the hospital after drowning while fishing in a nearby river.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company's on-site office.
Police said villagers threw stones at police, so officers fired warning shots.
But the riot mobile unit (Indonesian paramilitary police) began to shoot into the crowd, and one person was killed.
Domingu Buddy, 29, told Time magazine, "We were all panicked and now we're scared that they're going to retaliate." "He lived near the hospital and witnessed the wounded being rushed to the hospital.
"I hid at home for two days. ”
The Dhay parliament has called for the police involved to be brought to justice and for the mobile riot units to be withdrawn from the area.
Pania has always been a place of right and wrong for the Indonesian government.
The lack of effective development has fostered discontent among the me, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes, scattered in the lush central highlands of Paniai.
Many joined the Free Papuan Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans by dispersing raids and raids to kidnap Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top leaders of the Free Papua Movement were born in Paniai, including Tadius Yugi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result, thousands of Panai have been arrested and deliberately detained by the military in recent years under the guise of "safeguarding national sovereignty".
Some never showed up again.
In the eyes of Papuans, Pania is a "forgotten land of tragedy".
Poverty breeds resentment.
The rice sold in Enarotali is so small that the locals simply can't afford it.
Bread is simply out of reach.
The people here grow everything they can eat: mainly sweet potatoes and some fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is a woman's job, and each woman can take care of four or five sweet potato fields.
They usually keep most of the harvest for domestic use, and sell the rest at the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes are worth only 10,000 rupiah (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality has widened among local Papuans and new immigrants, whose numbers have increased significantly since the opening of the new route to Nabire airport.
The few jobs that exist often go to better-educated and wealthier immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital or the necessary skills to run a competitive company.
John Gobay, president of the Paniai Tribal Council, said, "Young people don't want to stay in this village...... Because there is no work and no money here. ”
Papua is isolated.
In addition, restrictions on international media coverage remain tight.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudi and Basel Longchamp were expelled from Papua because they "did not cooperate with the relevant agencies", even though they had obtained rare filming authorizations.
According to Felim Kane, deputy Asia director at Human Rights Watch, Jokowi's election vow to lift reporting restrictions to promote transparency and development has not been fulfilled.
"If foreign journalists try to cover Indonesia's easternmost disgruntled provinces, Papua and West Papua, they are at new risk: visa denial and blacklisting," he said in a statement. ”
The absence of media surveillance means that international pressure on the Indonesian government has been largely confined to Papua's neighbors.
In March, six Pacific countries – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands, Solomon Islands – asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "all kinds of widespread human rights violations" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries also supported the Free Papua Movement.
Indonesia's Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Armanata Nasir, who was unfazed by the group's accusations, told reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia is still democratic and has a free media, so evidence of human rights violations is difficult to cover up." ”
Locals want more attention from foreign governments.
When Dutch human rights ambassador Keith van Barr led a delegation of officials to visit Jayapura on May 4, the local people broke their silence and pleaded, "We want to be free," according to a person familiar with the matter. He also attended that meeting, but asked for anonymity.
Indonesia will hold its next presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
The chairman of the tribal council, Gobay, said that "Jokowi's intentions were good, but he was surrounded by people who were involved in the Paniai shooting." ”
He wanted Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai not only live under the threat of a greedy army, but also have nothing, that the area has little education and poor public health care.
Gobay said that the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, believe that the vote they cast for Jokowi is a debt that he must repay.
"They don't need money, they need justice," he said. ”
Even under threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting made one last symbolic resistance: burying the body of a victim opposite the military police post.
They know that justice may never come, but at least they won't let the culprits forget their crimes.
Yukabus bowed his head and said, "My family was killed,
What else can we do?"
