The fire once again engulfed Dubai's "Torch" skyscraper
On Friday, a fire broke out in one of the world's tallest residential buildings in Dubai, forcing hundreds of residents to flee the 337-meter-tall, 79-story supertall building.
This is the second fire to sweep through a high-rise building in just two years, and it happened to happen in the skyscraper known as the "Torch".
The building has been evacuated, no injuries have been reported, and no cause of the fire has yet been discovered.
"We were sleeping, and then we were woken up by the fire alarm and people started screaming.
We ran down the stairs, and it took about 50 minutes to run down from the 10th floor," a resident named George told Reuters.
Dubai's civil protection authorities said the fire brigade extinguished the fire at around 4 local time (0000 GMT) and is cooling the building.
The government said it was working to provide shelter for those affected.
The accident could reignite concerns around the world about the safety of façade materials used in high-rise buildings.
An investigation conducted by the management of the Torch skyscraper after its 2015 fire found that most of the damaged objects were cladding façade panels for decoration and insulation.
British police have said they believe problems with the insulation and cladding system at the Grenfell building in London may have been responsible for the rapid spread of the fire in June, which killed around 80 people.
