The survey found that more than one in five U.S. travelers carried prohibited items on board
A survey of airplane passengers found that more than 20 percent of passengers had intentionally or unintentionally carried illegal items on board through a Transportation Security Administration checkpoint, and at least 6 percent of those passengers had unintentionally carried prohibited knives or other bladed objects on board.
Less than 1% of passengers claim that they only found out afterwards that they were travelling with a firearm, ammunition or explosives by mistake.
The survey, which looked at more than 1,000 people and was conducted by charter service Stratos Jet Charters Inc., also found that younger travelers were more likely to blatantly ignore the rules.
19.7% of respondents who admitted to intentionally carrying TSA-prohibited items on board were millennials, compared to less than 15% of Gen Xers.
The most common items that deliberately slip past TSA security personnel are food and beverages.
More than 3% admitted to knowingly carrying a bladed object through security, while 2.2% of female respondents and 3.7% of male respondents also said they had intentionally carried illegal drugs on board.
The company said the survey was conducted to understand the number of people who accidentally carried and deliberately carried prohibited items through plane security to board the plane.
Not surprisingly, the people most likely to carry the contraband through security – intentionally or unintentionally – are those who fly the most.
However, the company points out that the TSA guidelines are a bit complicated and difficult to understand.
People are often unsure of what and how much liquid they can carry.
So it's no surprise that the TSA seized the most of the banned liquids.
At one point, it was thought that the TSA might have made books an embargo.
Liquids are allowed on domestic flights, but not on international flights.
EPA Administrator Pruitt has changed his mind about Obama-era emissions reduction regulations
A day after being sued by 15 states, Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Scott Pruitt reversed his earlier decision to delay the implementation of Obama-era regulations to reduce smog air pollutant emissions.
Pruitt proposed the change because the EPA was able to respond more quickly to the needs of state agencies that regulate the environment than previous administrations.
He did not refer to the legal challenge brought by the Federal Court of Appeal against his former office.
At issue is the October 1 deadline for states to begin meeting the 2015 ground-level ozone standard.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would defer compliance by a year to give the Environmental Protection Agency more time to study the plan and avoid "interfering with local decision-making or hindering economic growth."
Prior to his appointment by President Donald Trump, Prutt was Oklahoma's attorney general and had long opposed the strictning of environmental regulations.
Since arriving in Washington, Prutt has repeatedly turned to blocking or delaying regulations that the chemical and fossil fuel industries oppose.
Wednesday's abrupt reversal is the latest legal hurdle on Prut's regulatory rollback agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the Environmental Protection Agency had overstepped his authority in trying to delay enforcement of the Obama administration's rules requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt offered a U-turn on ozone standards, saying that the Environmental Protection Agency would strengthen its commitment to work with states to adopt a complex process to reach new standards.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet a specified deadline and then waited for activist groups and others to sue before agreeing to an agreement to set a specified timetable," Prutt said. He has filed more than a dozen prosecutions against the Environmental Protection Agency in his previous work.
"We don't believe in regulation through litigation, and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take regulations and authorities seriously. ”
Still, the EPA's statement said Prutt may again use his "extension authorization and all other legally available authorizations" to ensure that the regulations are in line with "good policies and the best information available."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a sweeping overwrite of the ozone layer ordinance.
The House bill, approved last month, seeks to delay the implementation of the 2015 rule for at least eight years.
This measure has not yet been voted on in the Senate.
New York State Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, leading a coalition of states this week to sue the EPA, saying it intends to maintain legal pressure.
"The EPA's reversal – after we filed the lawsuit – is a significant victory for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers, with more than 115 million American communities directly impacted by smog emissions," Schneidman said. ”
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, and the District of Columbia have all joined New York in the case.
Ground-level ozone is formed by the reaction of common pollutants emitted from automobiles, power plants, oil refineries, chemical plants, and other sources in the atmosphere when exposed to sunlight.
The resulting smoke can cause serious breathing problems for sensitive populations and cause thousands of premature deaths each year.
Of course, public health advocates and environmentalists cheered Prut's astonishing transformation.
Lori Ann Byrd, of the Centre for Biodiversity, said: "It is disturbing that this common-sense measure is under tremendous pressure from the heads of departments who protect the air we breathe. ”
"We must fight the Trump administration's ideological campaign to cater to polluters and special interests to the end. ”
