Moore Beach Massacre: Activists recreate racist lynchings to deliver justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury rumbled past a crowd of onlookers in the small town of Monroe, Georgia, toward the tiny Moore Beach Bridge.
The car was carrying four black passengers and a white driver, and before the car reached the bridge, a group of white men with guns stepped forward and blocked the car's path.
The leader of the mob – a middle-aged man in a pinstripe suit – took a deep puff on his cigar and glanced into the windshield.
The passengers in the car were full of fear.
"We want - Roger!" the man shouted.
"Drag him out of the car!"
A young black man was dragged out of the front passenger seat, screaming to pierce the silence.
Fortunately, this horrific scene on July 22 was just a reenactment.
But when "Roger" put a noose around his neck, almost all of the onlookers let out a real gasp.
Since 2005, civil rights activists have returned to Moore Beach Bridge to recreate the night two black couple—Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Merley Dorsey—were lynched and hanged by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946.
No one has ever been charged with murder.
"Even though we know who they are, and even though we've seen them in the community, it's incredible that none of them have been arrested over the years," said Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the reenactment.
"This is a stain on history, a burden on our souls. ”
Brooks, 71, is a former Georgia congressman and lifelong rights activist.
For him, the reenactment is a compelling call to action, reminding the Monroe community every year that injustice has never been redressed.
"We want to prosecute, we want to close the case, we want to heal, we want reconciliation, but we have to get justice first," he said.
"Unless we get justice, we will not be healed and reconciled. ”
On July 27, 1946, the coroner covers the body of a Moore Beach lynching victim with a sheet.
According to FBI archives obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected of involvement in the lynching.
But none of them have ever been prosecuted.
While the suspects have been at large for a decade, civil rights activists say the dual motives for lynching are well known throughout town: political and sexual.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling allowed black citizens of Georgia to vote in the primary for the first time later that summer.
According to the FBI, around the same time, black sharecropper Roger Malcolm assassinated white landowner Barnett Hearst in a fight — what looks like it was for a woman.
Brooks said the rumor in town was that Hearst slept with Malcolm's wife, Dorothy, and that her baby wasn't her husband's.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, prominent white landowner Roy Harrison released Malcolm from prison on bail for $600.
Dorothy and his cousins, Mai Merry and George Dorsey, accompany him to prison.
But when they returned from prison and were approaching the Moore Beach Bridge, a group of lynchers surrounded the car.
"It turns out that it was Harrison who organized and ordered the execution of this murder," an FBI report concluded.
"It is clear that there was a conspiracy between state and local law enforcement who not only participated in the murder, destroyed the evidence, but also concealed the identities of the witnesses. ”
Brooks is very concise and to the point.
"This is a voting rights tragedy," he said. ”
"They were killed, and it was the killers who sent a message to the black people in this community: 'If you sign up and vote, you're going to do the same.'" '”
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Green has been in charge of leading the annual re-enactment of the Moore Beach Bridge lynching.
Her approach is vivid, gripping, and has a deeply racist background. Many people hope that this racism no longer exists in the United States.
It's hard to watch, and it's even harder not to look, but Green says that's the key.
"We don't want to talk about lynching, because lynching puts us in front of the ugly side of everybody," she said.
"But if you don't listen to me, or if you don't hear me talk about my experiences, I can't have a relationship with you. ”
This year's show began in June, with nearly 30 actors on the first day — a dozen whites, the rest black — huddled into a room to hear Green deliver a rehearsed overview of the show.
Wade Malbow served as Green's co-director.
He has played the role of the Ku Klux Klan for years, but he says the role has never been easy.
"I feel dirty because I'm not that kind of person," Malbow said.
"But I think it's very important to keep this history alive because we don't want to go back to that era. ”
In the room, actors Darios Bradshaw and Nick Lascone, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hurst, rehearse their lines.
The scene begins with Malcolm yelling and pushing Hearst away, angry that he slept with his wife, Dorothy.
"I say, get out of my place!"
Rascona shot back.
Then they fought.
Then everyone (at least all the black actors) burst out laughing.
Green laughed the hardest.
"What's wrong?!, Lascone asked.
He was panicked and confused.
Am I playing too far?
"No," Green said with a laugh.
"I just don't think white people say 'ah' when they fight back. ”
"Yes," another black actor quipped.
"Your tone has to be tough. ”
In this way, the energy in the room changes, and the feeling of camaraderie drives away the discomfort.
Everyone made an effort to do so, not only to put on a show but also to honor the memory of the four victims.
The scene started again.
This time, Rascona said the "ah" in a sharp and powerful tone.
Not a single one laughed.
The reenactment ended forcefully and quickly.
Screams, gunshots, and then silence.
A woman dressed in funeral black stands next to the actor's body, singing Billy Hallotte's eulogy "Strange Fruit".
Her voice drowned out the others.
A hundred yards away, about forty spectators were wiping sweat and tears.
The audience was almost evenly split between black and white.
There was a couple who came from Ithaca, New York, to see the show, and many others lived near the road.
Brooks took them to Malcolm and Dorothy's grave for nearly eight hours, all enduring the uncomfortably hot and humid heat of Georgia.
Until this point, the murderer remained a mystery. But now, standing on the same land where lynching took place, anxiety is in the air.
When the last note of the song disappears, Green asks people to come closer to examine the actor's corpse.
The children leaned down, looked at fake blood and corpses, and whispered to each other.
"They're not really dead," a young boy muttered to himself, as if reminding himself.
After a few minutes, Green thanked the crowd before the show ended.
The actor shook off the lynching rope and wiped away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Malbow, the man in a suit who plays the leader of the Ku Klux Klux Klan.
Nick Rascona hugged his two colleagues and wept in their arms, and the emotion of the performance eventually caught on to him.
"It's okay," one of the women whispered.
"We know you're not like that in your heart.
You do it for a reason. ”
Afterward, the audience sat down to dinner with the actors.
At the same table, a white couple from Atlanta chatted intimately with a black couple they had just met, chatting about the reenactment.
Dennis Duplinsky has a hard time finding words to describe how she feels after watching it.
"It's hard to imagine those horrible words and deeds...... It's people like you who say it and do it, because they look like you," she said.
"It really made me think that lynchings were still going on," she added, "and now it's just called a police shooting." ”
In the room, Tyrone Brooks sat at a table watching, tasting and reminiscing about civil rights.
He said he was already planning for next year's performance.
"Reenactment is an inspiring way because it describes the horrors we've experienced, but it's also very educational," he said.
"If you don't learn from it, it could happen again.
Those who do not study and do not understand their own history are doomed to repeat the mistakes of the past. ”
