US press: Scientists from the Chinese Air Force Engineering University study laser satellites for the removal of space junk
Reference News Network reported on January 18 that Chinese scientists have put forward a bold and innovative proposal to use large lasers to clean up the cluttered earth orbit and destroy old satellites and their sky garbage.
According to a report on the website of Newsweek on January 15, researchers from China's Air Force Engineering University wrote a paper entitled "Research on the Orbit Change Model of Space-based Laser Removal of Small-scale Space Debris", which describes how space debris can be irradiated into smaller, less harmful debris by laser through the use of space-based platform lasers.
Space junk has been a concern for the International Space Agency for years, and NASA has considered a variety of options for tracking, detecting and removing man-made debris, the report said.
Large-scale space debris can be removed by means of giant nets used to sweep and collect waste, as well as magnets that can be used to suck them out of orbit. Chinese scientists conducted laser simulation studies and came to the conclusion that this would be an effective way to clean up the Earth's orbit.
"[The simulation study] provides the necessary theoretical basis for the application of space-based platform laser debris removal technology," the abstract of the paper says. ”
A 2014 study by US defense giant Lockheed Martin found that there are about 200 threats per day for satellites in orbit.
High-velocity debris moving along Earth orbit is seen as a serious threat to future space missions and has been described by experts from the European Space Agency as a "deadly chain of threats". Over the past year, high-velocity debris has continued to increase.
According to a report on the website of Popular Mechanics on January 17, space is basically empty, but the space next to the Earth is becoming more and more crowded. Every satellite we send into space eventually turns into yet another piece of debris orbiting the Earth, and that debris builds up over time.
The more debris, the higher the chance that a satellite that is still functioning will be hit by debris, damaging or destroying a multimillion-dollar investment.
According to the report, all space agencies have plans to remove space junk in the future.
NASA is considering deorbiting the debris with a jet of gas, Europe is considering launching a satellite carrying a large net to capture the debris and bring it back to Earth, and Japan's idea is to capture the debris with an electric chain.
Now, China is also proposing a solution to space junk by using a large laser to knock floating space junk into small, less harmful pieces.
According to a paper published in the German monthly journal Optics by a group of researchers from China's Air Force Engineering University, installing such a laser on a satellite would be effective enough to clean up space, at least according to the simulation results.
The only way to confirm effectiveness is to conduct tests, and there are no arrangements for such a mission, but perhaps sooner or later someone will install a laser on a satellite and send it into space, the report said.
Once that happens, we can finally start eliminating the problem of space junk once and for all.
(Compiled by Hu Jing, Wang Haifang)
