The latest results of the Swedish Asylum Asylum Seeker Age Assessment Test have been released
The latest results of the Swedish asylum test, which uses the latest methods to medically assess their age, show that more than 80% of subjects are judged to be over 18 years old, but not everyone is convinced of its accuracy.
The Swedish National Forensic Science Centre (Rättsmedicinalverket) started the test earlier this year.
After allegedly failing to accurately assess the age of some refugees claiming to be minors, the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) designed these tests with a view to providing a more accurate age assessment during the asylum process.
So far, 6,880 testers have been sent to the Swedish Migration Service, and the Forensic Science Centre has now published the results of a total of 2,481 testers between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
80% (2002) were judged to be 18 years of age or older, although in another 25 tests, the Swedish National Centre for Forensic Science determined that the subjects were "likely to be 18 years of age or older".
In 432 tests, the result was that the person was "probably under 18 years old."
The test is only for people whose age is in doubt.
According to John Granson of the Center for Forensic Medicine, these results are consistent with those of previous months.
