How do the financial rules of football affect Neymar's move to Paris?
The rules aimed at preventing unrestricted spending by Europe's biggest football clubs will not prevent Neymar from moving from Spain's FC Barcelona to France's Paris Saint-Germain (PSG) for a record price.
As a result, the Union of European Football Associations (UEFA) has imposed further relegation on Paris Saint-Germain Football Club. The UEFA Union is the governing body of European football competitions and has the power to ban teams from participating in the highly-watched Champions League.
The introduction of the Financial Fair Play Rules (FFP) by UEFA in 2011 meant that Paris Saint-Germain would eventually have to prove that Neymar's transfer was funded without causing huge losses.
FC Barcelona has already paid €222 million ($262 million) just to cover the Brazilian player's release from his contract, while Neymar's salary will run into the tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial implications of Neymar's move to France.
Considering that the team is funded by the deep-pocketed ruling family of Qatar, Paris Saint-Germain could certainly sign Neymar for cash and add him to other star-studded teams.
Clubs can spend huge sums of money on players, but they must use legitimate sources of income to make up for the huge sums of money that will allow them to break even on football-related businesses.
The Financial Fair Play Rules were conceived by Michel Platini after he was elected president of UEFA in 2007.
The former Frenchman believes that for clubs that are heavily in debt in pursuit of success, they are actually cheating and risking the destruction of the club if the banks or all the owners withdraw their support funds.
In 2011, the focus of the Rules shifted from club debt issues to club loss monitoring.
This change means that Roman Abramovich's business model when he bought Chelsea FC in 2003, which was to buy a club with potential and then spend huge sums of money to improve the team and build a global brand, is now in a more demanding position.
In the three-year Rule evaluation period up to 2018, the club could lose €30 million.
Although Abu was disparaged by the then-president in 2015, UEFA successor Aleksander Ceferin remains committed to stopping excessive spending.
"Of course the Rules are not lapsed yet, and we will definitely strengthen the regulations in the future," Andrea Traverso, UEFA's manager for the Rules, told The Associated Press last week.
While Paris Saint-Germain will pay Neymar's buyout clause in a lump sum, it can also allocate the amount for accounting purposes during the term of the contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year deal, so the transfer fee could show up as €44.4 million in the annual account for the next five years.
The first wave of Rule sanctions, imposed in 2014, resulted in Paris Saint-Germain Football Club, as well as Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City FC, being the most severe sanctions.
Paris Saint-Germain FC was fined €60 million ($82 million at the exchange rate at the time), which was later reduced to €20 million, and asked for the 2014-15 Champions League season when the team reduced the number of players to 21 instead of the normal 25.
UEFA is eyeing clubs that try to increase their revenues by tying up their owners, defrauding financial regulators.
While companies in Qatar can sponsor Paris Saint-Germain Football Club, UEFA will not consider the sponsorship as legitimate income if the amount of the sponsorship is deemed to exceed the standard market price.
This is what happened in 2014, when UEFA ruled that Qatar Tourism's sponsorship of Paris Saint-Germain Football Club was overstated.
According to reports, a portion of Neymar's income at Paris Saint-Germain could come from payments from the Qatar 2022 World Cup organizing committee.
However, both Paris Saint-Germain and the organising committee have denied that Neymar will be an ambassador for the World Cup, and it would have been easy for UEFA's regulator to make such a move.
The recent sanctions imposed on Paris Saint-Germain mean that UEFA will be more vigilant against any attempts to circumvent the rules.
UEFA has not held pre-discussions with Paris Saint-Germain about Neymar's transfer, according to people familiar with the matter on Thursday.
All of the above individuals were contacted by the Associated Press only in an anonymous capacity, as they were not authorized to discuss the situation at Paris Saint-Germain Football Club.
The last published accounts showed that Paris Saint-Germain FC had an operating income of €542.4 million in 2015-16 and a profit of more than €10 million.
The accounts for the previous fiscal year have not yet been published.
Paris Saint-Germain expects Neymar's arrival to be a boon for sponsorship campaigns, franchises and jersey sales.
The club expects revenue to grow by at least 30% after signing Neymar.
Apparently, the Spanish league was furious to see the departure of one of the most famous players, trying to block Neymar's move and claiming that Paris Saint-Germain FC had violated the Rules.
La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS that "this is a clear example of 'financial doping', that the club and the country are the same", referring to Qatar, which has ultimate ownership of Paris Saint-Germain football club.
Arsene Wenger, the head coach of the Arsenal team, which is owned by an American sports mogul, has reservations about the attitude of the state-funded club and La Liga.
"It's a consequence of ownership, and it's completely changed the whole ecology of football over the last 15 years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"Once the country has a club, then anything can happen.
This will make it very difficult to comply with the Rules, as there are many different ways or various interests for a country to require big-name players to represent a country. ”
