The UK's National Health Service (NHS) has given the green light to controversial HIV medications
After the dust settles on the High Court's decision on NHS drug funding, patients will be able to access "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September.
NHS England has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a medication that can be taken before sex, has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by around 86% in high-risk groups. Health services will now deliver the drug to an estimated 10,000 people through a three-year initial trial.
It agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld the High Court's ruling last year. The ruling said the NHS was entitled to pay for PrEP despite NHS claims that local authorities should fund the drug.
The move, announced on Thursday, was called a "major new intervention" by NHS chief executive Simon Stevens, while the National AIDS Trust (NAT) described it as a "pivotal moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to register. More clinics will join in October, followed by full implementation across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a type of HIV medication that is taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Trials have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before having sex means that there are enough specific medications in the body to prevent HIV infection.
This medication can be taken every day or two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay, gay, bisexual men, transgender people, and positive HIV carriers who have not been successfully treated.
The clinic will identify eligible participants who have consented to the trial, including males, females, transgender individuals, and those whose sexual partners' HIV status is unknown on antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and are registered with a GP can also sign up for a sexual health clinic in their local area.
The scheme will cost £10 million, while the NHS England branch has signed a contract to procure the medicines this week following an international competitive purchase.
The trial aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how it is localized, absorbed, and administered on a large sample basis.
"This major new intervention should complement and strengthen HIV prevention broadly and successfully," said Mr. Stevens.
This is another milestone in more than 30 years of actions worthy of progress in addressing major human health challenges. ”
Deborah King, chief executive of the UK AIDS Trust (NAT), said: "This is a critical moment in the fight against AIDS.
If it does target people in need and at risk, then PrEP offers the potential to change the AIDS epidemic in the UK.
Starting in September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to a new and approved tool that can be implemented on its own, without consultation with a sexual partner, through this NHS-funded trial in England, which will make a difference in the lives of many people.
We applaud this announcement with both hands. ”
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrance Higgins Trust, said: "The priority now is to ensure that trials roll out quickly across the country and that no one is left behind.
Now that we've purchased the PrEP trial, we're ready to protect more than 10,000 people at high risk for HIV. ”
Shadow Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: "After months of postponement and government delays, the start of the PrEP trial is welcome and should have arrived sooner.
Evidence shows how transformative this drug can be made as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the spread of this deadly infection.
This trial will give us a closer look at the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that this trial be rolled out nationwide as soon as possible to protect people exposed to HIV and to help us go one step further to ending the spread of HIV in society. ”
