High quality of living: Applying lofts and clever design to transform a small apartment at Earls Palace into a spacious home
Joanne Ray is a former banker who is passionate about renovating her home, and in 2014 she moved from her big house in Knightsbridge to a small apartment at Earls Palace.
The apartment is located on the first floor of an elegant Queen Anne terrace – Joanne sold it without packing her bags, which is a testament to the new design.
"Before that, my ex-boyfriend and I lived in a bigger house in Knightsbridge," says Joanne.
"I was looking for a house with the right offer.
I saw this apartment at the Earls Palace and it also has high ceilings.
I liked it and made an offer on the same day. ”
Since its first viewing, the 1,000 sq. ft. apartment has now been completely renovated.
The apartment was originally a studio with a complex layout – one had to walk through the kitchen to the bedrooms – and Joanne wanted to add storage and a loft to make the most of the ample ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, plenty of light.
That's what I'm asking for," she said.
To do this, she hired Erfan Azadi from Duck&Shed Architecture and Design Studio (in Notting Hill) to take advantage of the 12.5-foot ceilings to create a home. This home is not only a development but also where Joanne lives.
The height of the ceiling was not high enough to add two upper and lower spaces, so the challenge was to create an attic that was tall enough for people to stand on.
Erfan had to think creatively in order to solve this problem.
"The steel structure is quite complex," he explains.
"We had to arrange the space so that it was displayed up and down without shrugging our shoulders and hunching our backs.
It's not just about building a simple platform, it's about starting the steel so that it's about the right height for the function. ”
With this arrangement, Erfan was able to acquire two full-length rooms in the space – which could add a lot of interesting elements.
The attic features vintage copper windows by the Retrouvius brand and overlooks the charming living area.
Gold furniture with mirrors, small silver pieces of furniture and Serge Mouille vintage lighting set the overall style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in adding atmosphere, space, and light.
Installing mirrors at both ends of a short hallway can make it look longer.
In the kitchen, a mirrored splashback is like a window to another room.
In the entryway, a small compartment with a mirror provides Joanne with storage space for cutlery and glassware.
The beautiful living room has an inviting sense of space and the ability to put away the kitchen when it is not in use.
Folding kitchens are not new.
But the uniqueness of this folding kitchen is a garage-style lift door.
"There's some engineering knowledge involved here," Erfan explains of the reinforcing veneer MDF door.
"It's a balancing principle, so when you push the door, it's easy to slide. ”
Thanks to clever use of space and storage, Joanne gained an additional 16 square meters, an extra bedroom, and an improved layout.
"At the end of the day, you're selling the size of the house -- or the valuation of your property is based on the size of the house," Erfan said.
"Basically, a real estate agent walks into a room and calculates it based on the size of the floor. ”
They will manage to increase the floor space while using high-quality materials, which will give the space a luxurious feel.
"The materials are hand-picked by you, so it helps create an emotional bond in your home." ”
"You won't fall in love with the power supply on the wall.
These things are important, but they won't tug at your heartstrings. ”
It turns out that with good design and the addition of extra square footage, a standard apartment can be transformed into a wow one.
In fact, you might choose to live like Joanne.
