The two brothers staged a battle for a $500 million real estate empire
Forty years after the Italian family founded their dynasty, the two brothers battle it out for more than $500 million, one of Victoria's largest real estate empires.
Colin De Lutis, a former director and developer of Carlton Football Club, lives in a mansion in the Tukara district, three doors away from his brother Paul. The latter took him to the Supreme Court over the division of their immovable and business assets.
Paul had wanted to break away from the family business since 2014, but the two brothers had a heated argument in the Supreme Court over the split.
Together, the brothers and their mother own 38 real estate properties valued at more than $500 million, which the family has built since the family bought Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded the Westco Jeans company, which grew to a retail chain of 160 stores.
In 1999, the company sold for $85 million.
After that, that money is put into real estate. Currently, the de Lutis family's portfolio includes city office buildings, Brunswick and Sorrento developments, Gold Coast and Mt Buller apartments, and suburban shopping centres.
According to an agreement with his late father, Colin, whom his brother Paul called the "main promoter and dominant figure" of the de Lutis family, owned about two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul accounted for about one-third.
Documents filed with the court say that Colin owned property valued at $316 million, while Paul owned property valued at $176 million.
Paul argues that the division of immovable property and cash proves to be the crux of the negotiations.
"Colin's proposed property division left him with what I consider to be the best property », he wrote in a first court affidavit in 2015.
Last Friday, the Supreme Court held its first hearing after several failed mediations.
Now, the two brothers are still fighting for control of the existing business, and Paul says Colin has kicked him out.
Colin denied this and accused Paul of poor management of certain properties.
In an early affidavit submitted by Colin, he expressed a desire to resolve the dispute.
"My Italian tradition dictates that family is the most important option. My Italian origin dictates that family is the most important ", he wrote.
The cost of the case continues to climb, and there are also hundreds of pages of affidavit, emails, and corporate reports filed by firms such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners, Charter Keck Cramer, top law firms such as Allan Myers, QC, and senior lawyers hired by both parties.
Ms. de Lutis and her late husband, Luigi, were both Italian immigrants. They started running mass eateries and delicatessens from the late 50s of the 20th century and bought a shop in Braunschweig in the early 70s of the 20th century.
They used collateral to buy Collingwood property, where Colin opened the family's first jeans store.
Colin said, "When I was a junior in high school," he founded Westco, "Paul was very young (about 10 years old) at the time." ”
Ana de Rutis said that she and Luigi, who died in 2012, wanted to pass on the property to their son in peace
"Luigi often told me that he never wanted his brothers to end up in court," she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer members of the De Rutis Group, and Colin said Mark paid him $10 million and Luke $26 million when he left the company.
Paul said that both Luke and Mark were "unhappy with the terms of their division of property."
According to TV star Eddie McGuire's biography published in 2015, Colin has kept a low profile despite being a former member of the AFL club's board of directors.
Fairfax Media reached out to Colin and Paul, along with their lawyers, on Friday.
However, only Colin replied via text message. Because the case has already been brought to court, he said, "I can't really say much." ”
"It's very, very sad that my brother Paul chose to sue me and take our family affairs to court", he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a court filing that he had tried to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father didn't want to see Paul and I end up in a dispute like the one we have now," he said, adding that he "still has hope that the dispute will be resolved." ”
On Friday, that hope seemed dashed.
"Our problems will be resolved through the courts in the near future", Colin wrote.
