A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two and a half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, 20, will serve 15 months in prison, which can be converted to probation. An additional 5 years of probation is added.
Carter was convicted in June of whether or not to commit intentional non-premeditated murder against Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at Thursday's hearing: "My family is heartbroken.
My son is my best friend. ”
While awaiting appeal, Carter was granted personal liberty.
She faces up to 20 years in prison, but her team of attorneys believes both she and Mr. Roy are mentally ill.
At the time of the sentencing, Carter was standing, wearing red trousers and a beige blouse, his hands clasped, his eyes tearful and his gaze downward.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy," prosecutors told the court.
"She ended his life in order to live better for herself.
She did not take responsibility ", said the prosecutor.
She didn't show any remorse. ”
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a terrible consequence, and she deeply regretted it." ”
However, Judge Lawrence Moniz said he did not find that her "age or maturity, or even her mental illness, would have had any significant impact on her conduct." ”
A prosecutor read a statement from Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, who said, "Not a day goes by that I don't grieve the loss of my beloved son."
I want him to be proud of me and what I've done. I am trying to stand with his sisters in all my pain that will stay with us forever", the statement said.
Mr. Roy's sister, Camdyn Roy, testified that she was "in a trance" because she realized she could never attend her brother's wedding or be his child's aunt.
"Losing someone who has been with me since I was born is a pain that I will live with for the rest of my life. She said.
This case seems to set a legal precedent because Massachusetts law does not make it a crime to encourage others to commit suicide.
Roy was found dead of carbon monoxide poisoning in his car in 2014, the year Carter was 17 years old.
Carter's text message revealed that she had encouraged him to commit suicide, and the case sparked national attention.
"There are many ways to hang yourself, jump off a building, stab yourself. She said in several text messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was on vacation with his family.
In the period before he committed suicide, she wrote, "You need to do this, Conrad," and "all you have to do is start the generator, and then you will be free and happy." ”
Judge Moniz said Carter used Mr. Roy's death to garner attention and ordered her not to profit from the case through any media.
There was a divergence of legal opinion in this case.
One of the few people who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was accused of murdering her British roommate in Italy in 2007 and acquitted two years later.
In an op-ed published in the Los Angeles Times, Ms. Knox, 30, said, "Michelle Carter deserves compassion and help, not imprisonment." ”
