The market size of China's self-driving tourism in 2020 may exceed one trillion yuan
In the context of consumption upgrading and the prevalence of independent travel, self-driving travel is encouraged by national policies and loved by more and more consumers.
But at the same time, the self-driving travel market, which is expected to exceed the trillion scale, is also facing double challenges.
In the context of consumption upgrading and the prevalence of independent travel, self-driving travel is encouraged by national policies and loved by more and more consumers.
However, at the same time, the self-driving tour market, which is expected to exceed the trillion scale, is also facing a double challenge: on the one hand, the development of the self-driving tour industry is not proportional to the market demand, and the self-driving tour organizers such as self-driving tour clubs and travel agencies are facing the dilemma of meager profits, and on the other hand, the infrastructure and services faced by self-driving tours are still in their infancy.
It accounts for 60% of the total number of domestic tourists, and the market size is expected to exceed one trillion yuan
In 2016, there were 4.44 billion domestic tourists, and self-driving tours accounted for about 60% of the total number of domestic tourists, and the market size of self-driving tours is expected to exceed one trillion by 2020.
According to the statistics of the number of self-driving trips by the China Tourism Vehicle and Cruise Association, the number of self-driving trips has continued to grow in the past five years, and the proportion of the number of trips in the number of domestic tourists has remained stable at more than half.
At the same time, the emerging field of self-driving travel has shown more attention and support at the regional and national levels, and from 2016 to 2017, policies and regulations related to self-driving, motorhomes and camping tourism have been intensively introduced.
In July 2017, eight departments, including the National Tourism Administration and the General Administration of Sports of the People's Republic of China, jointly issued the "Development Plan for Automobile Self-driving Sports Camps", and in the same month, 14 departments including the National Development and Reform Commission and the Ministry of Finance jointly issued the "Action Plan for Promoting the Development of Rural Tourism (2017)", in which self-driving tours were highlighted.
The introduction of the policy provides opportunities and policy guidance for the development of domestic self-driving tourism.
The self-driving tour club has a meager profit, and the complete industrial chain is the key
Although the domestic self-driving tour market has huge potential and the national policy is actively guided, the self-driving tour industry is still in its infancy.
According to the "2016-2017 China Self-driving Tour Annual Development Report", there are thousands of domestic self-driving clubs, car clubs, car clubs, etc., but the proportion of tourists who arrange self-driving travel accounts for the majority, and the proportion of tourists participating in various institutions such as car clubs and self-driving tour clubs is only about 15%.
At the same time, there are only a handful of online travel companies and traditional travel agencies that independently develop self-driving travel products, and many online travel platforms only sell self-driving travel products provided by some suppliers, and some self-driving travel clubs are also important suppliers.
From the perspective of organizing self-driving tours, it covers many aspects of "eating, living, traveling, traveling, shopping and entertainment", with a high degree of fragmentation, heavy upstream supply chain, and large randomness of tourist consumption.
Li Guanjie, founder and CEO of Beijing Xingtianxia Automobile Club, believes that self-driving tour clubs are similar to travel agencies in nature, and the main profit models in the early days were mainly offline activities, and the core point was self-driving tour line products and tour leader services.
However, in the field of self-driving tours, the homogeneity of route products is serious, and the service level of tour leaders is uneven, and self-driving tour clubs are facing the need for transformation again.
It can be seen that self-driving tourism itself is not an independent industry, but with the displacement characteristics of self-driving tourism, it has formed a cross-regional and industry-specific ecosystem, and it is very important to form a complete industrial chain.
Experts point out that in addition to basic tourism consumption, experience is a more important consumption element.
Therefore, for the development of the self-driving tour industry, the experience characteristics should be enhanced, and the theme of "self-driving tour +" and the IP of self-driving tour products should be developed.
Scenic byways are more than just roads, and car camps should not be just about food and lodging
In the face of the rise of self-driving tours, the basic development of self-driving tours is also relatively rudimentary.
Li Guanjie pointed out that the tourist scenic road is not just a road, but the need to integrate the elements of traffic and tourism in it, but the road repair and tourism itself are two departments to be responsible, the transportation department to increase the tourism elements, but also stay in the construction of toilets, consultation centers, propaganda columns and other facilities, and the combination of tourism is not high.
Compared with the well-known self-driving tour route "American Highway 66", the construction experience is worth learning.
The design of the scenic byway is no longer the most direct and fast path between the departure place and the destination, but follows the design concept of "experiencing the fun of driving", providing self-driving tourists with the best enjoyment of enjoying the beautiful scenery along the road;
In addition to scenic byways, the campsite is also an important supporting facility for self-driving tours.
However, among the self-driving tourists that the Beijing News reporter knows, there are not many consumers who choose to stay in the camp.
They believe that many camps are biased towards infrastructure construction, which can only meet the needs of food and housing, and the grade is not high, and the products are single, which cannot meet the needs of self-driving tours, which contain many elements.
Some industry insiders who did not want to be named said that many enterprises in the camp in the past few years were for the purpose of taking land, and after taking the land, the supporting infrastructure construction and services in the later stage have not kept up, and many of the operating conditions are losses, and there is no capital injection in the later stage, so it is difficult to do some corresponding supporting products.
Consumer groups
According to the data released by the China Tourism Automobile and Cruise Association in 2017, from the perspective of age, the self-driving travel group is concentrated in 21-40 years old, especially 31-40 years old, this part of the population has a certain economic foundation, and the demand for personalized tourism is high, and most of them are parent-child travel customers.
According to the accommodation survey, self-driving travelers are relatively more likely to prefer non-standard accommodation.
From the perspective of self-driving travel types, surrounding self-driving is the most important type of self-driving travel, accounting for 84.32%.
Outbound self-driving is the yearning of many people, but the proportion is still small.
At the same time, with the increase of consumer demand, tourists who used to like to "visit scenic spots" by car have begun to change their concepts, no longer "getting off the bus to take pictures, getting in the car to sleep" in the process of self-driving travel, but paying more attention to the experience and process of travel.
Dinosaurs use camouflage to evade enemies
At first glance, it looks scary, but it looks like a statue.
Researchers have unveiled the first study of an unbelievable rhinoceros-sized fossil found by Canadian miners, noting that the fossil is so well preserved that experts have dubbed it the "Mona Lisa of the dinosaur world."
The fossil is so well preserved that it can even be concluded that its scaly skin is reddish-brown in color. This indicates that it has had some "troublesome experiences".
A report in the journal Current Biology described it as "the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever discovered and one of the finest dinosaur specimens in the world." ”
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaurus that lived in the Middle Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its state of preservation has shocked researchers, who described it as "truly breathtaking".
According to National Geographic, the herbivorous armor dinosaur fossil is the best-preserved dinosaur of its kind ever discovered.
The fossil was discovered on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk while mining at the Suncol Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
At that time, he came across something that didn't seem quite like the rocks around him, so he decided to take a closer look.
The fossils he found were then sent to the Royal Tyrell Museum of Paleontology in Canada.
It took researchers six years to reveal the beast hidden inside a 2,500-pound (1,100-kilogram) clod of dirt.
After all this hard work, the final results are only now being announced.
"If you look at it, you'll almost believe it's sleeping," says Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum and lead author. The creature is on display in the exhibition hall
"It will be one of the most beautiful and well-preserved dinosaur specimens in the history of science - the Mona Lisa in the world of dinosaurs. ”
Researchers studying its skin found that the herbivore, while wearing armor and resembling a walking tank, could have been under significant threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaurs used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and used a technique known as "anti-shading", which is also used by many modern animals.
Experts say that in this way, it is better able to integrate with its surroundings and thus avoid enemies, suggesting that it was preyed upon by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature, a member of the nodulosaurus family, first made headlines in May and is currently on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
After 7,000 hours of meticulous unmasking of the behemoth, a museum technician who was part of the team, researchers are now studying it and naming it "Borealopelta markmitchelli."
The specimen was so well preserved that Dr. Mitchell, along with an international team of scientists, was able to document the patterns and shapes of the scales and armor on his body.
They discovered "anti-shading", a common form of defense in the animal kingdom, which means that the creature's back is darker than its sides.
Although "anti-shading" is common, the results of the discovery are surprising because the size of this dinosaur far exceeds that of existing animals that have undergone anti-shading.
This dinosaur was under pressure to be hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs and thus evolved in an advantageous direction, allowing it to hide in the confrontation as a means of survival.
However, most of the animals that survive to use anti-shading, such as deer, zebra or armadillo, are as small and fragile as their prey, suggesting that the creature is under real pressure to survive.
"The frenzied predation of large, heavily armored dinosaurs shows how dangerous carnivorous dinosaurs were in the Cretaceous," says Brown.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in its scales also indicates that the dinosaur's skin was reddish-brown in color.
Scientists are continuing to study the creature's life cues, including the stomach contents it retained, to find out what it was going to eat last.
They believe that the dinosaurs fell into rivers when they died, were subsequently washed into the sea, and finally sank to the bottom of the ocean in a back-down fashion.
At the time, Alberta's climate was as warm as it is in southern Florida today, and rivers and oceans may have gone deeper inland than they do now.
"This nodular dragon is truly amazing because it is completely covered by preserved scaly skin, and it has been preserved in dimensional space to this day, allowing its original shape to be preserved," Brown said. ”
As a result, the shape of the organism is almost identical to that of the Cretaceous period.
You don't need to use much imagination to reconstruct it, and if you look at it, you'll almost believe it's sleeping. ”
The Cretaceous period was the period when large, bipedal theropod dinosaurs roamed the earth.
Although the Tyrannosaurus rex was the king of dinosaurs, it did not appear until millions of years after the armored dinosaurs. The armored dinosaurs may have been hunted by some of the ancestors of the Tyrannosaurus rex.
They include the tall spinosaurus, a giant beast that weighs up to 6 tons and is 38 feet (11.5 meters) long.
The latest findings of scientists appearing in the journal Current Biology believe that the nodular dragon was washed into the sea after its death, after which mummies formed in the dirt.
On March 21, 2011, Sean Fink excavated the creature at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray, Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, with the skin and armor in the area from the nose to the hips intact.
The creature is about 18 feet (5 meters) long on average and weighs up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
It has two 20-inch-long sharp corners that protrude from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that the herbivorous armored dinosaur was active in what is now Western Canada before being washed into the sea by a flooded river.
However, the dinosaur's burial at the bottom of the sea allowed its armor to be preserved.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remaining skin is still covered with the bumpy nail pieces on the dinosaur skull.
As Michael Greshko writes in National Geographic, this level of preservation, like winning the lottery, is rare.
The more I looked at it, the more I thought it was incredible.
Fossilized skin remains still covering the mottled armor on the dinosaur skulls.
Its right forefoot is located on its side, and its five toes are spread upward.
I can count its nails. ”
