How do activists learn to answer the question: "Whose street?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrer was in turmoil.
On the first day of her trip to New York City, the St. Louis native sat in her Airbnb rented bed and browsed Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled upon a post from a high school student.
It reads "Police just killed an 18-year-old child who was still lying on the street".
She was confused when she noticed that no one else had posted the message on the feed. She closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
An @TheePharoah user kept pushing her a dynamic times.
The St. Louis area rapper tweeted live about Michael Brown's death. Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man, was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown's body, which had lost his vital signs, lying on the street for four hours.
"Crazy," Ferrer thought to himself.
But death is nothing new for her and her community.
She put down her phone and didn't open Twitter again until that evening and read a tweet about a crowd gathering on Canfield Avenue.
There were police footage and photos of people shouting, and a photo of someone claiming to be Brown's father that read, "Police in Ferguson just killed my unarmed son!"
She saw a live feed message of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another police officer held up his rifle and screamed, "I'm going to kill you all...... Beast. ”
"It wasn't normal," Ferrer recalled.
"It's not what we take for granted and what we can call typical murders. ”
At that moment, I shuddered.
I was angry and cried. ”
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two would head to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrer and Ferguson over the next three years was the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Street?", which was released in theaters on August 11.
It's a story about survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience from the perspective of the people who live in this neighborhood and fill the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrer drove to Ferguson with his daughter (in a floral dress and tiara accessories), the two revisited a topic they had discussed countless times before that morning — "about the black experience and the black condition."
"Do you remember when I taught you when blacks had to fight for what they believed in?" she recalled.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, which is not right.
I had to take her with me," Ferrer said later.
"What happened today is what happened in the past...... High tide.
She wants to know, to see, and to rise from it.
Not only does she need to be well-developed in terms of activism and organizing, but she also needs to understand the different dimensions of the Black experience and the Black condition, and understand what we must do to be free and liberated.
Even though I had the privilege of providing her with experiences of racism that she hadn't experienced firsthand, she was no different from other black girls.
If I protect her in this matter, I feel like I'm hurting her. ”
Their first stop on arrival in Ferguson was at a venue opposite the police station on South Florisan Road. The activists waited until Officer Darren Wilson finally did not charge the case, and the site became their camp.
Ferrer and her daughter got in touch with a local business owner who made bagged lunches.
They prepared the bags and were responsible for passing them to the protesters.
Slowly, Ferrer began to develop a new type of activism.
"My activism changed completely after August 9. As an undergraduate at Missouri State University, St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Nurse-Student Association, focusing on food justice and health disparities in the Black community.
"I have no organizational experience.
That's how it all came. ”
A few weeks later, Ferrer met with the film's co-director, Sabah Fleiyan, at a night parade.
Fleiyan said she and her director of photography, Lucas Alvarado Faller, "just wanted to document" what happened.
A question crossed Ferrer's mind: "Do you want to record or find a story that you can use to your advantage?"
This suspicion stems from many of these cases: people — often white — enter a community to benefit from its pain and tenacity.
As Fleiyan explained in a recent interview, "We've heard that people born and raised in Ferguson aren't focusing their voices, and we wanted to do it differently. ”
Fleiyan has been linked to co-director Damon Davis. Daemon Davis is a regional artist known for his activism against death row inmates.
His involvement led Ferrer and six other locals to join the "Whose Street?" project team, which remained with Brown for years after his shooting.
"This documentary is not about someone speaking for us or talking to us, it's what we say. Davis said.
"I mainly focus on how these characters are presented, because that's how I'm presented. ”
Although the goal was not to focus on Ferrer's experience — but to show that the movement was "not about messianic leaders, but about community cohesion," Fleiyan said — she proved to be the most open among the film's participants.
As a result, "Whose Street?" surprisingly chronicles Ferrer's personal life, such as falling in love and getting married.
"I felt naked," Ferrer laughed when he first saw the finished product.
"But I understand that there has to be a certain level of vulnerability to do this work and humanize black people. ”
In addition, Ferrell's story reaffirms and reorients the role of Black queer women in the broader Black Lives Events movement.
Two of the movement's three founders — who created #BlackLivesMatter on social media after the 2012 shooting of Black teenager Trevone Martin — identified as queer.
"Black queer women in leadership in general underpin the movement," Ferrell said, "and that's because we're constantly fighting on multiple fronts."
Black queer women have to endure it all. ”
Fleiyan agreed, mentioning that "this movement really has the support of Black women and a lot of Black queer women." ”
Because of her identity, Ferrer was chosen as the centerpiece of the film. However, she insisted that "this is not an affirmative action for the sake of things".
"She's the one who inspires that energy," she said.
"Although she is on the front line, it is no coincidence. Because in life at these crossroads, you have a lot to do as a Black queer woman.
Through the screen, you can feel her energy. ”
Meanwhile, in Ferguson, the press cameras are long gone, but the tense racial tensions between the community and the police remain.
Ferrer was sentenced to more than two and a half years of probation for trying to block a highway during a march.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere in the area she calls home: "It's a mess. ”
Still, since taking to the streets of Ferguson three years ago, she has stuck to the hymn she has worked so hard to remember.
"We have a responsibility to fight for freedom.
It's up to us to win.
We must love each other and support each other.
We have nothing to lose, except the shackles on our bodies. ”
