Similarities: The artist uses Chelsea Manning's DNA to create portraits
In the center of the pavilion at the Friedman Museum of Art in New York are multiple faces: white, black and brown, each with an almost imperceptible resemblance to each other, which are tied by cords hanging from the ceiling.
The 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg using cheek swabs and hair scraps sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent hair crumbs from Fort Leavenworth prison where the former intelligence analyst was sentenced to serve 35 years for leaking classified diplomatic cables through the WikiLeaks website.
The exhibition opened on August 2 with the title "Similarities".
It was the culmination of two years of correspondence between Dewey Hagberg, a well-known dissident who had been imprisoned and had sex reassignment surgery in prison, with Manning, who combined his discipline with his own in technology, computer science, and the arts. Former U.S. President Barack Obama pardoned the rest of her sentence three days before the end of his term.
Algorithmically analyzed from Manning's DNA, 30 portraits of "probable appearances" were created. Heather-Dewey-Harburg made a scathing and slightly unforgiving comment on this. His comments are as much about the polymorphic nature of DNA as they are about the concept of identity itself.
Manning, who was born by the name Bradley Edward, has publicly admitted to identifying himself as a woman during puberty. He was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including six counts of espionage law violations, computer fraud, and theft.
In prison, her image is suppressed, with only one photo, a grainy black-and-white selfie, looking visibly uneasy, sitting in the driver's seat and wearing a platinum-blonde wig.
In 2015, Heather-Dewey Harburg achieved great success with her 2012 project, Stranger Visions.
In that work, she used DNA extracted from detritus from forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum to create 3D portraits of people who might look similar.
That's when she happened to receive an email from Paper Magazine.
"They wanted to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and needed a portrait," Heather Dewey Harburg told the press at the opening of the exhibition.
At the time, Chelsea Manning couldn't visit or take pictures, so they contacted Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in making a DNA portrait.
As a result, the artist and her imprisoned muse became impossible pen pals, exchanging many letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic book, The Depressed Headshot, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo. The comic book envisaged that the president would grant Manning privileges in the future, and that she would be able to see the exhibit while she was in prison.
And Obama demanded her release just days after the book was published. It may have been a coincidence, as Manning was in his seventh year at the Kansas Military Penitentiary.
