Enchanted "New Retail"
Chen Xinlei and Yang Kaihan: Amazon's announcement of its entry into bookstores and grocery stores when it squeezed into the world's top 10 retailers is interesting in terms of timing and motivation.
In November 2015, Amazon opened its first brick-and-mortar bookstore in Seattle, followed by two more in Portland and San Diego.
At the beginning of 2017, Amazon opened stores in New York and plans to have at least eight storefronts by the end of the year.
Almost at the same time, Amazon announced the trial operation of its unmanned supermarket (Amazon Go), customers do not need to queue up when they arrive at the store, and they do not need to check out, they can scan the code at the door, take the desired goods and leave, and the shopping amount will be automatically deducted from the customer's Amazon account.
As far as Amazon is concerned, it is very unexpected that it has suddenly made frequent moves in physical stores in recent years.
Because as early as 2007, in the "Open Letter to Shareholders", CEO Jeff Bezos emphasized that Amazon will not easily open a physical store unless the following four conditions are met at the same time:
1. We must be confident that this new opportunity will give shareholders a return on their investment;
2. We must be convinced that this new opportunity is of great significance to the company as a whole;
3. We must be convinced that this new opportunity is being ignored by the market;
4. We must be convinced that in this market, we have enough resources to make customer-facing differentiation.
Bookstores and grocery stores are the most shaky of the two brick-and-mortar retail categories, and they are also the first rivals to fall after Amazon's rise.
Amazon's announcement of its entry into these two physical markets at a time when it is squeezing into the top 10 retailers in the world is interesting in terms of timing and motivation.
Does Amazon's approach contradict the assurances in the shareholder letter?
A similar sound was heard on the other side of the globe. On the morning of October 13, 2016, at the 2016 Hangzhou Apsara Conference, Jack Ma, Chairman of the Board of Directors of Alibaba, delivered a keynote speech.
"Starting next year, Alibaba will no longer mention the term 'e-commerce'," he said.
The era of pure e-commerce will soon come to an end, and there will be no e-commerce in the next ten or twenty years, replaced by 'new retail'.
The combination of online and offline and logistics will produce new retail. ”
For a while, the three words "new retail" seemed to have been magical, and they were frequently on the lips of people in the industry.
But what exactly does "new retail" mean?
If it only refers to the combination of online and offline, then the concept is not new.
In 2016, eMarketer tracked 180 of the largest e-commerce companies and estimated that total e-commerce sales were about $200 billion, with the top 25 accounting for more than $159 billion.
Of these 25, 18 are traditional retailers that have only started online in the last five years (such as Macy's, Nordstrom, Target, Gap, etc.).
Alibaba Group's 28.3 billion yuan stake in Suning Cloud Business is also vivid.
Globally, retailers and e-commerce companies are moving from a single channel to an omnichannel retail system that spans brick-and-mortar stores, e-commerce, mobile and social media.
Could it be that Ma Yun's "new retail" is more of a summary than a prospect for the future?
If not, then what is the difference between the concept of omni-channel and "new retail"?
Perhaps, the key to the problem is not whether online and offline will be integrated, but how.
Looking back at the past 20 years in the retail industry, the rise of e-commerce, like the rise of discount retailers in the early years, has focused on price and convenience.
Relying on these two pain points, e-commerce has moved products with a very high degree of standardization, such as books and CDs, from offline to online.
With the development of online consumption habits and the continuous improvement of customer experience, e-commerce has extended its tentacles to other categories and began to improve efficiency.
In the words of Daniel Zhang, CEO of Alibaba, "Using the ideas and technologies of the Internet to comprehensively reform and upgrade the existing total of about 30 trillion social retailers, so that the escalating consumption needs of Chinese consumers can be effectively satisfied, and the entire process of commodity production, circulation and service becomes more efficient because of the extensive use of the Internet and big data." ”
Therefore, the road of e-commerce is a road that is asset-light on the surface and asset-heavy on the ground.
"Light" refers to the fact that the burden of fixed assets, staffing, and management processes is not as large as that of the traditional retail industry, while "heavy" refers to the huge investment required in logistics and warehousing.
The change of logistics mode ensures the high efficiency of e-commerce.
