Helping your company avoid becoming the next Uber startup
Amy Ehret once wanted to investigate employee happiness at her e-commerce startup, but the survey didn't help.
The responses are often vague, unhelpful, or even worse, deceptive.
Even though she promised anonymity, some employees still don't trust the process.
Madison Reed, a San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company that manages 75 people, says "the responses she gets are lacking consistency and objectivity."
So she called for help.
A new wave of HR startups has sprung up to help companies understand how employees are feeling.
They built and licensed software specifically designed to measure employee engagement, allowing companies to quickly conduct polls for specific teams and demographics, provide employees with anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass executives and report directly to the board.
"Now, you can track your health with tools like Strava and Fitbit, but where is the company's Fitbit?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Redwood City startup Glint. Glint software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Ehret says within three years, she has used Glint to gain more insight into what her employees are thinking and feeling.
In addition to quick surveys and polls for specific teams, Glint also provides company heatmaps of which units have the most complaints and which managers have low approval scores at a glance – which allows her to drill down into why.
Companies are starting to realize that they have to master their workplace culture so they don't become the next Uber. Uber was embroiled in a scandal after former Uber employees published a blog post describing the harassing environment and the speakers were punished by the company.
For a startup like Glint, this oversight desire is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to Let's Talk Payments, a financial technology analytics website, the global governance, regulatory, and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Convercent, a Denver, Colorado-based start-up dedicated to helping companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw an increase in interest and activity during Uber's reputational damage earlier this year.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a customer.
Like Glint, Convercent lets companies send customized "diagnostic" surveys, collect confidential responses in real-time, and view heat maps of their problem areas.
Convercent also offers an anonymous text hotline for employees to report bad behavior.
If the chairman is implicated, then the complaint will go directly to the board.
Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent, said: "The Court of Public Opinion usurped the power of regulators.
If a company is found to have mistreated or behaved unethically towards its employees, even if regulators don't intervene, the company could face high consequences of consumer boycotts, employee turnover and involvement in lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees in more than 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure employees understand work guidelines and procedures, and provide an easy way to contact the company's headquarters.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, they had to find the company's headquarters phone number or email, file a formal complaint, and expect the headquarters to take it seriously.
It's often a daunting and unsettling experience, says James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday's general counsel, who doesn't think there's a good way to track employee complaints.
But now with Convercent, the company can more quickly identify and address issues that executives in remote offices, cities, or states didn't know about — such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair wage practices.
"I get a closer, 360-degree view of the work experience," says Vitrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday's risk management team.
"We are protecting our shareholders from employment lawsuits. ”
After Andorra's accounting firm collapsed due to the Enron scandal for ethical violations, companies began to place greater emphasis on ethics, values and employee engagement in 2002, Quinlan said.
But it wasn't until "social media came into its own world" that companies realized they couldn't stop their revelations from going viral online.
"Before technology was used to monitor ethics, people looked at hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service and charge companies recurring fees for the use of their products.
This business model and business opportunity is supported by venture capitalists who are already supporting the two startups.
In February, Convercent raised $10 million in funding from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing its total capital to $47 million.
In November, Glint received $10 million in funding from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing its total funding to $60 million.
Given the interconnectedness of companies, cultures, and ventures, these investments can hardly come as a surprise.
A growing body of research shows that today's employees expect more from the workplace than ever before.
In a competitive market like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are just bets.
Employees want to feel accepted, valued, and feel that their time is spent with a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to be part of the company, feel that their voices are heard, and that the work they do is beneficial, they are more committed to making the company successful," said Nina McCartney, vice president of global benefits and employee experience at LinkedIn. LinkedIn uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors realize returns when their portfolio companies perform well, and companies perform well when their employees are loyal and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it's no surprise that they'll look for financial support.
Workplace culture experts say it's important to have employee engagement data.
However, this data is useless unless the company's administrators take action.
In fact, if a company asks for feedback from its employees, it can expect change to be underway.
If change doesn't progress fast enough, or if it doesn't progress at all, it can lead to disappointment and cause employees to leave the company.
Russell Ruth, head of consulting at Kotte International, a business management firm, said: "If you want to ask for 4,000 pieces of advice, then you need to be prepared for 4,000 conversations. He's seen the mistake of companies that rely too heavily on data collection.
"Because if you don't follow up all the way, employees are like, 'Did you really hear me?'
Do you care?
If you don't care, why should I care?'"
Ehret said Madison Reed, who now conducts monthly employee surveys, has been able to take action on the day Glint reported the issue.
After gathering feedback from employees about their frustrations due to the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to resolve the issue by restructuring the company's internal team and increasing communication training.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new insights into its employees, and in the long run, they want to make a shift in an industry known for its high turnover rate to better retain employees.
"If you're not committed to creating a culture of transparency, you're going to lose talent," Vitrano said.
"If you lose talent, you lose customers.
And when you lose customers, you lose companies. ”
