Create a graphic novel: The Story of an English Castle
More recently, the tiny Scottney Castle has been the protagonist in a compressed version of the music film, and for a time became a refuge for Mrs. Margaret Thatcher during the seventies and eighties.
But Scottney has witnessed 700 years of tumultuous history from the comfort of his comfortable location in the Belle River Gorge in Kent, and now it's the inspiration for a graphic novel written by Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire with a mop head with a penchant for historical documents.
"I can see the handwriting of the ancients 300 years ago, and I find it so beautiful," he says, with a wistful look in his eyes.
"What kind of interpersonal fate is it that makes this letter fall into my hands. ”
Spanning the Middle Ages and Edwardian times, The "An English Castle" book chronicles the various families that lived in Scottney, each with a story written by a different, future British artist such as Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer, and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not the first book in Rhodes to use archives as a raw material: he also wrote 2014 The Teeth of the Dead and Other Stories, a book inspired by British library documents, a work he completed with an uncontrollable creative passion.
"I couldn't restrain my urge to write from the moment I saw the thumb mark on the side of the letter, written by a double agent working for the Jacobites in the 18th century," he said. ”
"That's his fingerprint!
And the letters always smelled of smoke, because at that time, you needed to light a fire to have a light.
For us 300 years from now, the smell makes it feel like they're all around us.
Oh, I love archival documents!"
For those who are struck by the old paper, having the support of the National Trust and Arts Council of England and living in the castle for almost four months ("To be honest, I've been a bit long") seems too fantastic to believe it's true.
Rhodes spent several days touring Victoria's "new" castle, rummaging through archives and researching the estate's many treasures and curios, such as hyena heads hanging on the walls and bottles that had spent centuries in the moat.
He wandered the grounds and ruins of the old castle, chatting with wanderers, gardeners, and sometimes with the artists who drew illustrations for his books.
Then in the evening, he would "drink some whiskey and write." ”
Scottney's hidden history is not well understood, as the "National Trust" was only fully accessed after the death of its last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
Ten years later, when Rhodes arrived, the staff began to process the archives, which he described as "the aristocracy of hundreds of years ago was leaving: 'Oh, put it in the attic'." ”
Diaries, letters from the British imperial era, maps of the borders of various countries: "You would think that land disputes would be boring," Rhodes said, "but there would be two families fighting over a birch tree."
Let it go, guys!"
Some of the stories in the work use castles as a starting point to study English history more broadly, including The Labourer, which follows a man who left the newly built castle to participate in the peasant revolt of 1381.
"The story in the book, 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,' chronicles a riot in the castle in 1380," Rhodes said.
"The peasant uprising started in that area, and I think it was a good place to start an uprising.
Maybe there's a connection between the two?"
Other stories are deeply rooted in the castle's history, such as The Priest, which tells the story of the Darrell family's seven years of hiding a Jesuit priest during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, in which the protagonist of the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell is credited with giving himself a funeral by filling his coffin with stones (his coffin was discovered years later when it was revealed to the ground).
The Darrells is Rhodes' favorite family of Castle Scottney: "These gentlemen seem to be scoundrels, always borrowing money and paying for things they can't afford.
Generations of Darrell men have settled their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women, and I think they should be a handsome bunch of lads who know how to pursue women. ”
As his mission in the castle ends, Rhodes begins to look for other bizarre writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness writing a graphic novel about "El?¤m?¤nm?¤ki," an early 20th-century sanatorium that was slowly abandoned.
But Scottney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he said.
"It's like, 'Oh, I've got to deal with the real life of the trough cake. '”
