Just when you thought 2017 couldn't be weirder, a new report on technological developments was released in the field of sex robots.
Yes.
Sex robots are a big deal these days.
Recently, the Responsible Robotics Foundation (FRR) released a report that looks ahead to the development of sex robots over the next five to ten years.
According to Noel Sharkey, Emeritus Professor of Robotics and Artificial Intelligence at the University of Sheffield and co-founder of FRR, we need to start getting serious about the rise of sex robots.
Customers can choose the robot's eye color, nipple shape, and nail type.
"People are laughing behind their backs, but companies do have a lot of sex robots, and we're going to see more," Sharkey said at the release of the new report. ”
Modern sex dolls have evolved from inflatable dolls to robots, with silicone skin, warm to the touch, and deliberately using artificial intelligence to set up human-like sexual responses.
Users can also "customize" their robot to suit their preferences, with options ranging from eye color and nipple shape to nail type or color.
But what's even more disturbing is that many robots with "personalities" will make the "copy wife" look advanced.
Modern sex toys have evolved into robots with silicone skin.
RealBotix bots, for example, can be customized based on characteristics that the user finds attractive, such as shyness.
There's also the Roxxxy Gold sex robot, developed by True Companion, that presets personality traits, including the slightly shy "Cool Farrah" and the "adventurous" "Wild Wendy."
"The Roxxxy Gold bot has a personality that is as appropriate as possible to you," says True Companion's website.
So she loves what you love and hates what you hate.
She also had a little mood in those days just like normal people!
She can be laid-back, she can be talkative, and she can be 'sexually aroused'!"
There's a lot of uneasiness with the rise of sex robots — not just in place of real human relationships — but also the groveling feminity and the hint of rape twitching on the glamorous (interpreted: resistant) Farah are the most worrisome.
True Companion likens Roxxxy to a man's vibrator on its website.
The website says "If a woman has a vibrator, then why can't a man have Roxxxy?"
However, these sex robots are not just fetishes, nor are they just sex toys.
Their emergence and growing sophistication points to a darker, deeper part of our culture: an escape from perfect gender equality to sex with submission as an add-on.
Of course, most men don't have sex robots, and while FRR notes that sex robots are growing in popularity, they are still on the fringes of consumer culture.
But what seeps through the periphery allows us to see the course of our time.
A lot of people weren't weird or aggressive until the free market gave them the opportunity to be like that.
It's no coincidence that these delicate sex robots are coming at a time when women's rights are under threat across the globe, and that there's also a president in the White House who brags about sexual violence against women.
The most chilling part of the TV series "The Handmaid's Tale" is not the realistic picture, not the hanging corpse, nor the pair of gouged out eyes, but the overly real imagination.
The Republic of Gilead was a jump, but now it looks like it's not far off.
The goal behind these sex robots is to create as much of a body as technically possible that resembles a real woman's body (albeit in the proportion of a star).
The creators of these robots wanted them to have a human sense of touch and mimic real human movements.
But to put it bluntly, their "personalities" are not representative of real women.
They can't break up and they can't run away.
They have no recourse and no follow-up stories, no independence at all, and no possibility of breaking the illusion of total slavery.
In other words, they are sex slaves.
