Let Mitt Romney be the epitome of common sense
Political divisions polarize the American electorate and, from a micro perspective, undermine American family harmony. This is no surprise for the Trump era.
Around Christmas and Thanksgiving, major newspapers in the United States have been flooded with opinion columns about how to deal with the fear of voting for Trump's relatives.
It is generally believed that we are doing everything we can to puncture our "filter foam".
Even less vocal is Trump's power to bring his family together.
I mention this because my cousin, a left-wing poet living in Chicago who has a long-standing feud with Republicans in our family, is coming to visit me in New York this week.
She reminded me that coming together against a common enemy can have a powerful effect.
As a result of working with Mr. Trump in the White House, everyone she knew, even Republican relatives who had been in a political altercation for decades, were now suddenly and strangely on the same page.
If it's all at the table, that's certainly a good thing. But what strikes me is that from a broader perspective, this poses a significant risk.
While leftists have been egged on by Trump, the warping effect of his presidency has pushed us all to the right.
When we talk about "normalization" and Trump, we are referring to the possibility of worrying that his outlandish behavior may one day stop.
There is, however, a more worrisome long-term scenario in which Trump wants to "normalize" relations with right-wing Republicans who previously opposed Mr. President's standards and now suddenly look like a symbol of reason.
I've found myself nostalgic lately for Mitt Romney's version of the madness: putting the dog in the car, the 14 percent income tax (but at least we know his tax returns), both of which seem too minor for the offense compared to Trump.
After the Trump era is over, the next Republican candidate will only need to be sensible enough to qualify for immeasurable improvements.
