Do pork, dairy, and chocolate help with inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)?
Meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study shows the opposite: diets rich in meat, protein, and dairy can help relieve symptoms associated with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease affects the lives of about 1.3 million Americans and about 300,000 Britons, causing stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme tiredness.
Researchers at the University of Washington typically advise patients to avoid meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, but researchers have found that tryptophan, a key amino acid for protein, helps promote the growth of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explains that immune cells patrol the gut to ensure that harmful microorganisms hidden in food do not sneak into the body.
Maintain a balance between the cells that trigger inflammation and the cells that promote tolerance, protecting the body from damaging sensitive and delicate tissues.
Inflammatory bowel disease can occur when the equilibrium is too inflammatory.
In experiments, an immune-boosting cell was found to appear in mice carrying special bacteria.
Bacteria need tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to form the appearance of cells.
"We have made a link between a bacterial population (Lactobacillus reuteri, which is a normal part of the gut microbiota) and a population of cells that promotes tolerance," Professor Colonna said.
The more tryptophan a mouse consumes in their diet, the more immune cells they have.
He suggests that if humans use the same approach, the combination of Lactobacillus lucii and a tryptophan-rich diet might result in a more tolerated, less inflammatory gut environment.
Postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas studied a tolerant immune cell when she found that one group of study mice had such cells, but another group of the same strain was not kept separately.
She suspects that the difference has something to do with the gut microbiome (the bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract) community of mice.
DNA sequencing of cholesterol in mice showed that 6 bacterial populations were present in mice with immune cells, but not in mice without immune cells.
Mice are housed in a sterile environment, so they lack gut microbes and cannot present such immune cells, which are produced in the presence of Lactobacillus luci.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers cultured Lactobacillus luciferi in liquid and then transferred a small amount of bacteria-free fluid to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
This immune cell develops into a tolerant cell.
When the active ingredient is purified from a liquid, it can be proven that the active ingredient is a by-product of tryptophan metabolism called indole-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in rat feed, the number of such cells increased by about 50%, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells was halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people have the same tolerant cells as mice, and that most of us have Lactobacillus luciferi in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from Lactobacillus luciferi can be induced into cell development in humans like mice in experiments, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
"The development of these cells may be exactly what we want because these cells can control the inflammatory response on the inner surface of the gut," she said.
It can be said exactly, the presence of high levels of tryptophan in Lactobacillus lucii may lead to an increase in the number of this species.
