Today, let's talk about a more serious problem than buying a house: repaying the loan.
1. China's growing housing debt crisis
According to the data in the article, in November 2017, the National Finance and Development Laboratory of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and the National Balance Sheet Research Center released the "Report on China's Deleveraging Process in the Third Quarter", which pointed out that the leverage ratio of the residential sector continued to rise, from 47.4% in the second quarter of 2017 to 48.6% in the third quarter , up 1.3 percentage points, and 3.8 percentage points in the first three quarters of 2017.
The proportion of debt in the residential sector in the total real economy has increased, and the leverage ratio has risen rapidly.
Relevant studies have shown that the liabilities of Chinese households in financial institutions are mainly consumer loans, accounting for about two-thirds of residents' liabilities and about twice that of operating loans.
Among them, among the consumer loans, the medium and long-term loans mainly housing loans account for about eighty percent, but in terms of increment, short-term consumer loans have grown rapidly, which is higher than that of medium and long-term loans.
In addition, China's household debt ratio only counts the total amount of credit obtained by the household sector from financial institutions, and Chinese households also have a lot of private loans, including borrowing money from relatives and friends, and there is a large amount of hidden debt.
According to the statistics of the Suning Institute of Finance, the leverage ratio of Chinese residents was only 3% in 1996 and only 18% in 2008, but since 2008, the leverage ratio of residents has begun to show a rapid growth trend, doubling to 36.4% in just six years. By the third quarter of 2017, the household leverage ratio had reached 48.6%.
Let's compare another data, in May last year, HSBC released a survey report spanning nine countries with nearly 10,000 respondents.
The report surveyed young "millennials" (born between 1980 and 2000) in nine countries.
According to the report, China's homeownership rate among post-80s and post-90s youth is as high as 70%, far ahead of the second place Mexico (46%), and twice the level of the United States (35%).
These data tell us that there is a very likely problem, that is, the biggest potential "gray rhinoceros" of Chinese residents at this stage is estimated to be unable to repay their debts compared to those who cannot afford to buy a house.
2. Why is the housing debt crisis the most serious problem?
As we have analyzed before, although we have been saying that China's housing prices are high, compared to other countries in the world, China's homeownership rate is actually quite high, so instead of saying that housing prices are high and you can't afford to buy a house, I'm afraid that the question to ask many friends now is can you afford to take out a loan?
If we look at the real estate market around the world, China's real estate market started late, except for Hainan, which we mentioned earlier, there has not been a major real estate crisis, but just ten years ago, in 2008, the origin of the world's financial tsunami was the real estate crisis in the United States.
The cause of the U.S. housing crisis has been attributed to two houses: Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
At that time, in the golden age of the United States, real estate companies sold houses to low-income people in the United States with a very low down payment in order to expand sales, and when the American economy was good, the real estate market was also thriving, but the good times did not last long, as the growth of the American economy stagnated, causing the income of home buyers to decline, so a large number of household consumption expenditures began to decline.
However, at that time, the current situation in the United States was that the financial assets and real estate assets of the United States were the components of American household assets, and almost all the household assets of the low-income group in the United States were real estate, while most of the assets of the top 20% of the high-income groups were financial assets, so the more poor the real estate debt ratio in the United States.
A serious fact is that these people bought houses when the economy was better, so the money to pay the mortgage was also calculated based on their better income, and when the income declined, the pressure on the mortgage not only did not decrease, but even increased because some subprime mortgage plans became floating, so the real estate problems of these American families gradually evolved into a real estate crisis.
When the bank reclaims the property from the buyers who default on the loan, they will sell it at a very low price, which leads to a gradual decline in housing prices in the area, which in turn triggers a further decline in housing prices, forming a vicious circle, when housing prices fall to a certain extent, more and more buyers find that the value of their houses is even lower than their loans, so more people stop continuing to repay their mortgages, and cause more bad debts。
As a result, a huge vicious circle is formed:
"The economy is sluggish – incomes are falling – some people can't afford to pay their mortgages – banks are selling houses at low prices – house prices are falling – more people are stopping paying their mortgages – banks are selling again – house prices are falling again ......"
And the problem is not only that, because of the continuous decline in housing prices, everyone stops repaying the loan and gives the house to the bank, it is not that you have no debt, if the money you get from auctioning the house cannot repay the loan you owe to the bank, then you still need to repay the money, simply put, suppose you use a down payment of 600,000 yuan, a loan of 2.4 million yuan to buy a house worth 3 million at that time, when the house price falls to the house is only worth 2 million, you no longer repay the loan and give the house to the bank, after the bank auctions the house, you not only lose your down payment of 600,000, but also owe the bank 400,000 debts, you still have to continue to pay back。
As a result, under this vicious circle, the US economy gradually collapsed, which eventually triggered the US financial crisis in 2008.
Therefore, at this stage, the level of China's household debt ratio has reached a high level of 46.8% is a very vigilant problem, this data is still lower than the level of developed countries at present, but the signs of problems have begun to appear, the country has repeatedly emphasized the issue of deleveraging since last year, which is a very prescient judgment, if the household debt ratio is allowed to continue to rise, it will inevitably lead to huge risks, so we must strictly guard against the emergence of financial risks.
Therefore, with the positioning that the house is for living, not for speculation, the state has accelerated the establishment of multiple measures such as multi-subject supply, multi-channel guarantee, and simultaneous rental and purchase to further resolve potential risks.
For our individual families, we must give up real estate speculation thinking, buy a house within our means, to avoid their families falling into a huge burden, only a reasonable assessment of their income and debt level is a healthy family wealth development path.
Author: Special researcher of Suning Institute of Finance, financial columnist, financial commentator.
