White House props cost thousands
Last month, the White House decided to transport a Marine Corps helicopter to the South Lawn to showcase the great glory of American manufacturing at a cost of up to $24,000, according to military records published by Time magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D, also known as Marine One when the president rides, is a key exhibit at the White House's July 17 event highlighting U.S. construction projects.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and other senior White House officials toured manufactured products from all 50 states.
Exhibits include a Connecticut-made helicopter, a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire engine, and a Mississippi forklift.
According to records from the Marine Corps Helicopter First Flight Team (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter, the White House Military Office asked the helicopter to show up on daily order (FRAGO), i.e., just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn for this "special" event.
The day before the event, the HMX-1 commander stated in an email to the senior Marine Corps flight deputy commander, "I just want to make sure you know because this event is highly regarded." ”
The information indicates that the helicopter will arrive at the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. event and will leave only after the lawn is cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that day.
The message also said that in the event of a postponement of departure from the White House, a second crew would be required for the return voyage due to duty time constraints.
The original crew was on standby by the helicopter during the event, while the security forces were on standby nearby while the aircraft was on the ground.
The records obtained by Time magazine do not clearly indicate whether a second crew will eventually be needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
The record states that HMX-1 had inquired about whether the event violated the Act.
"One of the questions we asked was whether this violated the Hatch Act and were told there was no violation," the commander wrote. ”
"Sounds like you're locked up," the deputy commander replied.
The White House defined the "Made in America" event as an official event and therefore not governed by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president pursued health care reform, which was an issue in the Senate at the time, and touted control of government regulations.
The use of Marine One or Air Force One aircraft for propaganda purposes is nothing new.
Successive presidents have been required to travel on these planes.
However, it is not common to requisition it just for the purpose of taking pictures.
Trump was in the spotlight in February, in Melbourne, Florida, when the presidential plane slowly taxied and eventually stopped at the backdrop of his first campaign rally, while his Twitter account was flooded with complaints about the previous president's use of the plane.
"The White House is thrilled by this 'Made in America' exhibit, which showcases products from all 50 states made by American workers using American materials," said Deputy White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters. ”
HMX-1 crews often conduct flight training near the Washington area and on the South Lawn, practicing accurately placing the President of the United States in the White House.
During Trump's G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 practiced 58 landings at the White House.
The U.S.-made event flight counts toward this month's crew training requirements, an official said.
The helicopter unit also flew an additional 11 hours of "non-presidential support missions" that day.
The White House said taxpayers did not cover the cost of any of the other props at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in arranging the South Lawn helicopter display.
HMX-1 did not keep budget records for presidential flights, so it was difficult to determine the exact cost incurred by the event.
However, according to the Department of Defense's FY 2017 Hourly Cost Record, the VH-3D's DoD reimbursement is $24,380 per flight hour.
Force records recorded the duration of each flight of the aircraft from the base at the Marine Corps airfield in Quantico, Virginia, for 30 minutes.
The White House said the cost of operating the helicopter was much lower than the fee.
"It is very misleading to estimate what a taxpayer will pay based on reimbursable expenses," Walters said.
These estimated costs include personnel costs, maintenance costs and many other sunk costs that are included in the annual allocation.
A 2015 RAND study showed that DoD reimbursable expenses do not include personnel costs, but do include fuel, maintenance, and contracting costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spike defended the use of the helicopter for the event,
and said that "the idea is to show what is made in the United States this week,
And I know that both Sikorsky and Connecticut are proud of that, and they both contribute to our national security, and I guess there are hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think like most Americans, we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, the result of the hard work of countless Americans.
So it's certainly not out of place to show that. ”
It's unclear if Trump interacted with the helicopter during his tour of the South Lawn at the event, but he did get in the driver's seat of a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Mr. Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky and joked with the media about the company's planes he owned.
He said: "I know the Sikorsky aircraft very well. I have three. ”
