The General Labor Union (GMB) is looking at the investment in McVitie's Glasgow facility
The union wants the management of biscuit manufacturer Macrovita to commit to production at the Lasgow plant for the long term.
The Scottish branch of the CGT said it had been silent about the future of its investment in the Tollcross plant.
The plant employs more than 500 people and produces products such as hobnobs and rich tea.
Pladis, owner of Macrovita, said the company had invested more than £5 million in the plant over the past few years.
He added that if there is a change in factory operations, employees and union representatives "will be the first to know".
In a letter to the company's director, the Scottish branch of the CGT called on McVita to "resolve the problem of uncarried funds for the modernization of the production line." ”
Drew Duffy, senior organiser of the CGT union, said: "We were deeply concerned to our members because we were unable to get a clear picture of Tollcross's future business needs and investment plans from the general manager of the plant.
Generations of families have worked here, and the high concentration of labour in the local community and Greater Glasgow is an important pillar of decent employment in areas with high levels of unemployment and social deprivation.
So, from a job, pay and economic prosperity perspective, against the backdrop of Brexit, rising cost of living and a prolonged manufacturing recession, the eastern Glasgow region is in dire need of a growing Microvita production network. ”
A Pradis spokesperson said: "Tollcross's factory manager received a letter from the Scottish branch of the CGT yesterday and will be responding immediately as we value our ongoing engagement with our employees and union representatives.
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with staff and CGT representatives in Tollcross to openly discuss a number of issues.
We had discussions with our employees, and then, like all other companies operating in a highly competitive and economically uncertain environment, we conducted a review of our ongoing operating model applied to our businesses and factories in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years, we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross plant, particularly in line and operational improvements.
We are fully aware of Tollcross's historical position as a production site, and employees and union representatives will be the first to know about any changes to our operations at the site. ”
Tibet, 11 May (ZXS) -- Nima Tsering, deputy director of the Tibet Autonomous Regional Sports Bureau, said at the base camp on the north slope of Mount Everest on 10 May that in the future, the cleaning up of domestic garbage on the north slope of Mount Everest will move from a public welfare action in the past to a normalized behavior led by the Chinese government and with the participation of all sectors of the international community.
On May 10, environmental volunteers loaded sorted garbage into trucks.
Photo by China News Service reporter He Penglei In the past ten years, with the sharp increase in the number of mountaineering explorers and tourists on Mount Everest, the environmental protection problems in the location of the mountain have become increasingly prominent.
