London, Jan. 9 (Xinhua) -- The British Sports Council announced on the 9th its goal to participate in the Pyeongchang Winter Olympics in South Korea next month: to win at least five medals, which is the "most ambitious" goal in the history of the British delegation to participate in the Winter Olympics.
The British Sports Council is responsible for the allocation of funds for the Olympic sports and, of course, for the medal-winning targets for each event.
British athletes are expected to challenge for medals in snowboarding, curling, skeleton and short track speed skating.
In the past Winter Olympics cycle, the British Sports Council allocated a total of 32 million pounds (about 280 million yuan) of training funds for the Winter Olympics, which is double the Sochi Winter Olympics cycle.
Most of this money comes from the national lottery, and the rest comes from the state treasury.
Great Britain's hopes of winning gold are mainly pinned on two people, Alice Christie, a three-time gold medallist at last year's World Short Track Speed Skating Championships, and Liz Arnold, the women's skeleton champion last year.
At Sochi 2014, the British team won one gold, one silver and two bronze medals, their best record since the first Winter Olympics in 1924.
